body:
Ah. 

@raethlein, https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/commit/485ec8d64a1b2c6b6662ad140d99447a185d3bb2 changed `ScriptControlException` type from a `BaseException` to an `Exception` between 1.36 and 1.37, which is causing the reported behavior change by the users. I can't see a good reason why it _should_ be `Exception`, as it's functionally similar to a `KeyboardInterrupt` of sorts, which inherits from `BaseException`.

@Panosero the workaround here is such:
```python
import streamlit as st
# import streamlit_qs as stqs
import streamlit.runtime.scriptrunner.exceptions
import time

def counter():
    for x in range(3):
        st.write(x)
        time.sleep(1)
    st.rerun()


if st.button("notry"):
    counter()

if st.button("try"):
    try:
        counter()
    except streamlit.runtime.scriptrunner.exceptions.ScriptControlException:
        raise
    except Exception as exc:
        st.error(exc)
        # logging stuffs
        time.sleep(10)
        raise
```
The rerun exception still has to propagate up the call stack, but this shortcircuits the exception handling behavior when the exception is a ScriptControlException.
